INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'c375ccee-a17d-41fb-8758-cbae756650d6',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$axum Project Structure — Vertical Slices Beat MVC Every Time$escape$,
  $escape$MVC in axum leads to scattered logic: routes in one file, handlers in another, business logic somewhere else. As your app grows, tracing a single feature requires jumping across four directories. Vertical slices fix this by co-locating everything a feature needs.

Organize by domain: `src/users/`, `src/posts/`, `src/auth/`. Each module owns its `router()`, request/response types, handler functions, and any db queries. The top-level `src/router.rs` simply merges these sub-routers via `Router::merge()` or `Router::nest()`.

Handlers stay thin — they extract data from `State`, `Path`, `Json` extractors, delegate to a service or query function, and return a response type that implements `IntoResponse`. Keep that logic in a sibling `service.rs` or `db.rs` within the same feature folder.

Shared infrastructure (db pool, error types, middleware) lives in `src/infra/` or `src/common/`. Avoid a god-level `handlers.rs`. With vertical slices, adding a new feature means creating one folder and wiring one `Router::merge()` call — nothing else changes.$escape$,
  $escape$// src/users/router.rs
pub fn router() -> Router<AppState> {
    Router::new()
        .route("/users", get(list_users).post(create_user))
        .route("/users/:id", get(get_user).delete(delete_user))
}

// src/router.rs
pub fn app_router(state: AppState) -> Router {
    Router::new()
        .merge(users::router())
        .merge(posts::router())
        .merge(auth::router())
        .with_state(state)
}$escape$,
  $escape$rust$escape$,
