INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '0a186909-20ea-4e75-b96b-b2c7e4504569',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$axum Middleware — Pipeline Order, Global vs Route-Specific$escape$,
  $escape$axum builds its middleware stack on Tower's `Layer` + `Service` traits. Two attachment points control scope: `Router::layer()` wraps the entire router — including 404 responses — while `Router::route_layer()` wraps only the routes registered *before* that call. This distinction is critical: auth middleware on `route_layer()` won't fire on unmatched paths, avoiding accidental short-circuits.

Ordering is outside-in: the last `.layer()` call becomes the outermost shell, meaning it receives the request first. In practice, put `TraceLayer` last (outermost) so every request gets logged before anything else runs. Put compression before tracing if you want accurate byte-count metrics. Auth should sit closest to handlers via `route_layer()` so it only guards real routes.

For custom logic, `middleware::from_fn` accepts an async function with `(Request, Next) -> Response` — no manual `Service` impl needed. Access extensions with `req.extensions()` or inject state via `middleware::from_fn_with_state`. Avoid cloning heavy state inside the middleware fn; use `Arc`-wrapped state passed through `Extension` or `State` instead.$escape$,
  $escape$use axum::{Router, middleware, routing::get};
use tower_http::{trace::TraceLayer, compression::CompressionLayer};

async fn require_auth(req: axum::extract::Request, next: middleware::Next) -> axum::response::Response {
    if req.headers().get("authorization").is_none() {
        return axum::http::StatusCode::UNAUTHORIZED.into_response();
    }
    next.run(req).await
}

let app = Router::new()
    .route("/admin", get(admin_handler))
    .route_layer(middleware::from_fn(require_auth)) // guards /admin only
    .route("/health", get(health_handler))          // no auth
    .layer(CompressionLayer::new())                 // inner: after routing
    .layer(TraceLayer::new_for_http());             // outer: first in, last out$escape$,
  $escape$rust$escape$,
