INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '1e04b9ae-5e1b-4d03-a03c-0116b1a42472',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$axum Input Validation — Schema Validation at the Boundary with validator$escape$,
  $escape$axum doesn't ship built-in validation, but pairing the `validator` crate with a custom extractor gives you schema-level rejection before your handler runs. The pattern: wrap `Json<T>` in a `ValidatedJson<T>` extractor that calls `validate()` on the deserialized payload and short-circuits with a 422 if it fails. This keeps your handlers clean — they receive already-validated data and never see malformed input.

Define your input struct with `#[derive(Deserialize, Validate)]`, annotate fields (`#[validate(length(min = 1, max = 100))]`, `#[validate(email)]`, etc.), then implement `FromRequest` for your wrapper. On validation failure, serialize the `ValidationErrors` map into a structured JSON body — field name as key, error messages as array. Never return raw `validator` error output; normalize it into a consistent `{ field, message }` shape your clients can machine-read.

For sanitization, trim and normalize strings before validation, not after — a leading space shouldn't pass an `email` check only to be stripped silently downstream.$escape$,
  $escape$use axum::{async_trait, extract::{FromRequest, Request}, http::StatusCode, Json, response::{IntoResponse, Response}};
use serde::Deserialize;
use validator::{Validate, ValidationErrors};

#[derive(Deserialize, Validate)]
pub struct CreateUser {
    #[validate(length(min = 1, max = 50))]
    pub username: String,
    #[validate(email)]
    pub email: String,
}

pub struct ValidatedJson<T>(pub T);

#[async_trait]
impl<T, S> FromRequest<S> for ValidatedJson<T>
where
    T: for<'de> Deserialize<'de> + Validate,
    S: Send + Sync,
{
    type Rejection = Response;

    async fn from_request(req: Request, state: &S) -> Result<Self, Self::Rejection> {
        let Json(value): Json<T> = Json::from_request(req, state)
            .await
            .map_err(|e| (StatusCode::UNPROCESSABLE_ENTITY, e.to_string()).into_response())?;
        value.validate().map_err(|e: ValidationErrors| {
            (StatusCode::UNPROCESSABLE_ENTITY, Json(e.field_errors().clone())).into_response()
        })?;
        Ok(ValidatedJson(value))
    }
}

async fn create_user(ValidatedJson(payload): ValidatedJson<CreateUser>) {
    // payload.username and payload.email are guaranteed valid here
}$escape$,
