INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'e1235e70-226e-4886-9c34-bf7993c520e5',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$axum Dependency Injection — Manual Wiring with State<T> and Why It Beats Magic Containers$escape$,
  $escape$Axum has no built-in DI container — injection is manual, wired through `Router::with_state()`. Your `AppState` struct holds everything: database pools, HTTP clients, service traits. Handlers extract it via `State<AppState>`.

The testability key is trait objects. Instead of concrete types inside `AppState`, store `Arc<dyn UserRepo>`. In production, wire `Arc::new(PgUserRepo::new(pool))`; in tests, swap in `Arc::new(MockUserRepo::new())` — no mocking frameworks, just a struct implementing the trait. Your handler signature never changes.

`FromRef` keeps large state ergonomic: handlers declare only what they need (`State<Arc<dyn UserRepo>>`), not the entire `AppState`. Implement `FromRef<AppState>` for each sub-type and axum performs the split automatically at extraction time.

The tradeoff vs Spring or .NET's `IServiceCollection`: zero runtime reflection, zero startup magic, but you own every wire-up. Circular dependencies are a compile error, not a runtime panic. `AppState` must be `Clone` — which is cheap because it's all `Arc` pointer clones under the hood.

For integration tests, construct the full `Router::with_state(test_state)` — this validates routing, middleware ordering, and handler wiring in one shot.$escape$,
  $escape$use axum::{extract::{Path, State}, routing::get, Router};
use std::sync::Arc;

#[async_trait::async_trait]
pub trait UserRepo: Send + Sync {
    async fn find(&self, id: i64) -> Option<User>;
}

#[derive(Clone)]
struct AppState {
    users: Arc<dyn UserRepo>,
}

async fn get_user(State(s): State<AppState>, Path(id): Path<i64>) -> impl IntoResponse {
    s.users.find(id).await
}

// Wire-up: swap PgUserRepo for MockUserRepo in tests
let app = Router::new()
    .route("/users/:id", get(get_user))
    .with_state(AppState { users: Arc::new(PgUserRepo::new(pool)) });$escape$,
  $escape$rust$escape$,
