INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'daa82089-3a2f-4336-996f-f87c88f4dbb8',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$axum Dev Tooling — Hot Reload, cargo-generate, and Scaffolding Your Router Fast$escape$,
  $escape$axum has no official CLI, but the Rust tooling ecosystem fills the gap well. For hot reload, `cargo-watch` with `cargo-watch -x run` restarts your server on file changes — pair it with `tower-livereload` to push reloads to connected browser clients without a full restart. Add `RUST_LOG=tower_http=debug` to surface request traces immediately.

For scaffolding, `cargo-generate` lets you bootstrap an axum project from a template. The community template `https://github.com/rickfast/axum-template` wires up Router, SharedState, and Tower middleware layers out of the box. Run `cargo generate --git <template-url>` and you get a layered `Router` with typed state via `Extension` or `State<Arc<T>>`.

For code generation of repetitive handler boilerplate, `axum-macros` provides `#[debug_handler]` — this isn't scaffolding per se, but it surfaces mismatched extractor errors at compile time rather than runtime, dramatically shortening the feedback loop. Combine all three: generate → develop with watch → debug extractors at compile time.$escape$,
  $escape$# Install tools
cargo install cargo-watch cargo-generate

# Hot reload: restart server on any src change
cargo watch -x run

# Hot reload with browser push (add to Cargo.toml: tower-livereload)
# In main.rs:
let app = Router::new()
    .route("/", get(handler))
    .layer(LiveReloadLayer::new());

# Scaffold a new axum project from template
cargo generate --git https://github.com/rickfast/axum-template --name my-api

# Enable compile-time extractor diagnostics
#[axum::debug_handler]
async fn handler(State(db): State<Arc<Db>>) -> impl IntoResponse {
    StatusCode::OK
}$escape$,
