INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '885e799d-d511-4f6e-a21e-8071dc304ab8',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$axum Background Jobs — Channel-Based Task Queues with Tokio Workers$escape$,
  $escape$axum runs on Tokio, so background jobs are first-class citizens — no separate job runner needed for most workloads. The canonical pattern: thread an `mpsc::Sender<T>` through axum's `State` extractor and spawn a worker loop before starting the server.

Handlers enqueue work via `state.job_tx.send(payload).await` — non-blocking from the HTTP path. The worker task, spawned with `tokio::spawn`, drains the channel independently of request handling. Use a bounded channel (`mpsc::channel(n)`) in production — it applies backpressure and prevents silent OOM under burst load. Unbounded channels are a footgun.

For scheduled jobs, `tokio-cron-scheduler` runs inside the same Tokio runtime — no separate process. For durable queues with retries and persistence, `apalis` integrates directly with axum's `State` and supports PostgreSQL and Redis backends out of the box.

Graceful shutdown is non-negotiable: store the `Sender` in your axum state and drop it when a shutdown signal arrives. The worker's `rx.recv()` returns `None` and exits cleanly. Wire this into `axum::serve(...).with_graceful_shutdown(signal)` to drain in-flight jobs before the process terminates.$escape$,
  $escape$use axum::{extract::State, routing::post, Router};
use tokio::sync::mpsc;

#[derive(Clone)]
struct AppState { job_tx: mpsc::Sender<String> }

async fn enqueue(State(s): State<AppState>, body: String) {
    s.job_tx.send(body).await.ok();
}

#[tokio::main]
async fn main() {
    let (tx, mut rx) = mpsc::channel::<String>(256);
    tokio::spawn(async move {
        while let Some(job) = rx.recv().await {
            tokio::spawn(async move { process(job).await });
        }
    });
    let app = Router::new()
        .route("/jobs", post(enqueue))
        .with_state(AppState { job_tx: tx });
    let listener = tokio::net::TcpListener::bind("0.0.0.0:3000").await.unwrap();
    axum::serve(listener, app).await.unwrap();
}$escape$,
  $escape$rust$escape$,
